<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1865-08-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1865-08-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="321" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d321">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Adams</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1530.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1865-08-28"><hi rend="italic">August</hi> 28, 1865</date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            very interesting despatch o the 20th of July last, No. 1015, respecting
                            the favorable issue of the recent elections in Great Britain. We shall
                            look with much interest to the proceedings of Parliament, and the
                            tendency towards a policy just, if not friendly, to the United
                            States.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Charles Francis Adams,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>